<div1 type="trialAccount" id="t18440819-2132">
               <interp inst="t18440819-2132" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18440819"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18440819-2132" type="date" value="18440819"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18440819-2132-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-2132-18440819 t18440819-2132-offence-1 t18440819-2132-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>2132. <persName id="def1-2132-18440819" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-2132-18440819" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-2132-18440819" type="age" value="29"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-2132-18440819" type="surname" value="RILEY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-2132-18440819" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">JOHN RILEY</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18440819-2132-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18440819-2132-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18440819-2132-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="simpleLarceny"></interp> for stealing 38 gallons of brandy, value 7<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.; 12<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; the goods of the <persName id="t18440819-name-1102" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1102" type="gender" value="indeterminate"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18440819-2132-offence-1 t18440819-name-1102"></join>East and West India Dock Company</persName>, in a port of entry and discharge.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MESSRS. CLARKSON</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">and</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">BODKIN</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440819-name-1103" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1103" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1103" type="surname" value="BIGGS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1103" type="given" value="WILLIAM OWEN"></interp>WILLIAM OWEN BIGGS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am foreman of the vaults of the East and West India Docks Company, at the Limehouse entrance. I was at my post, on Monday, the 5th of Aug., at a quarter past six o'clock in the morning—the prisoner is a lighterman—I saw him coming out of the dock in his lug-boat, the <hi rend="italic">Orton</hi>, No. 774—my gate was the last he would have to pass before he got into the river—he ought to have produced a pass before he passed me—I asked him for one—he said he had not got one—his boat appeared empty—I said he must get a pass, or he could not go out—he came on shore, and went to get a pass—he would have to go to Anderson, the officer, at the south gate, for it—when he had gone I went into his boat, and, on lifting up the head-sheet boards, I found a number of bladders of brandy stowed away between the timbers of the boat, and a basket containing a gimlet, a cock, and centre-bit—he did not return to the boat—there is no business done in the dock on Sunday—I attend tide every day—I had seen the prisoner in the dock on Saturday evening, about a quarter to seven o'clock—that was past the time when, according to the regulation, any boat can go in or out—he had not his boat with him then—I had seen him on the Monday morning, before he came with his lug-boat—he was waiting till I opened the inner gates—he could not, according to the regulations, have had an opportunity of getting in at that early hour—my place opens at six—the Dock Company officers took possession of the brandy—Anderson came up, and assisted in searching the boat.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. DOANE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> When you saw him on Saturday evening, did you see his boat? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No—he ought to have gone to the right to get out of the dock, but he went to the left, towards the <hi rend="italic">Honduras</hi>, which was on the north side of the north quay—she was not the only vessel that laid there—I do not know whether this brandy has paid duty—I was not put into prison for smuggling—I have been in the Dock Company's service seven<lb></lb>teen years, and have risen to what I am from a labourer—I was in prison falsely for a very short time—they found that out afterwards—it was not for smuggling—it had nothing to do with brandy—I am not aware that I ever tasted brandy which had not paid the duty, I might have done it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BODKIN</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> What were you charged with? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I cannot tell—it is twenty years ago—I was admitted to bail.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440819-name-1104" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1104" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1104" type="surname" value="ANDERSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1104" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES ANDERSON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am watchman to the East and West India Dock Company. On Monday morning, the 5th of Aug., a few minutes before six o'clock, I saw the prisoner on the bridge leading over the lock to go to the Export Dock, and then I saw him in his lug-boat coming out of the Export Dock into the basin—I was at the gate—he asked me for a pass—I told him I would attend to him directly—he passed on to the outer lock, so that he got no pass—he went on towards the water-gate—he came back in a few minutes, and said, "I am come for my pass"—he was on land, without his boat—I said, "Come with me, and get it," it is my duty to examine the boat before I give the pass—I was going towards the water-gate for that purpose—he was with me—he turned his eyes towards the water-gate when he was on the import bridge—I looked the same way, and saw Biggs in the prisoner's</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184408190174"></xptr>
               <p>lug-boat—I do not know whether the prisoner saw him, but when I looked round again, he was out of sight—he had slipped away by some means—I proceeded to the water-gate, examined the boat, and saw the bladden, as described.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Is it not the usual practice to examine the boats, whether empty or full? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—we do not let any empty boats go out without—that is well known.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440819-name-1105" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1105" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1105" type="surname" value="HESELTINE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1105" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES HESELTINE</persName>
                  </hi>. I am an officer of the Docks. On the morning that the Orton was stopped I went on board her about seven o'clock, and found 43 bladders of brandy, measuring about 38 gallons and 1 quart—there were 13 gallons of dark brandy and 25 gallons and 1 quart of pale—I went on board the <hi rend="italic">Honduras</hi>, which was in the Dock—her cargo was brandy—I sounded some casks—one was "N. B. 957," and one other after—I found they were not full—three of the largest casks had been pierced with a centre<lb></lb>bit, and the centre-bit was found in the prisoner's boat—it would have made the holes—I tried it to the holes, and they fitted exactly—the holes were filled up with a cork—I have samples of each of the brandies here.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440819-name-1106" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1106" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1106" type="surname" value="COPPOCK"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1106" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>CHARLES COPPOCK</persName>
                  </hi>. I am an officer of the Customs, and am searcher at the West India Docks. On the 5th of Aug. I went on board the <hi rend="italic">Honduras</hi>, and found part of her cargo was brandy—I examined all the brandy there, and found 5 casks deficient—one of them was marked "N. B., 957," and was deficient 9 gallons, and there were 2 gallons deficient from one marked "D. G." with an "O." under it—there were 35 gallons deficient in the whole, some pale and some brown—I have tested the brandy that was in the casks and that in the bladders, and believe them to be the same.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440819-name-1107" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1107" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1107" type="surname" value="DAVIS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1107" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM DAVIS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am night-watchman in the Dock. I was in the Dock on the night of the 3rd of Aug.—the <hi rend="italic">Honduras</hi> was lying there—I saw the prisoner crossing the dock—I asked what he was doing—he said looking after his craft—it was after the men had knocked off work—I saw him there again at half-past seven in the evening.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Did you see any craft near the <hi rend="italic">Honduras</hi>? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> There were several there lying alongside—I saw three or four.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440819-name-1108" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1108" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1108" type="surname" value="SUMMERS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1108" type="given" value="RICHARD"></interp>RICHARD SUMMERS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am one of the coopers of the London Docks. I examine all casks before they leave the London Docks on the Brandy Quay—I examined all the brandies that passed from the London Docks on the 3rd of Aug., and on the 31st of July, I did not observe any tap-holes in any of them.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Do you know how many left the Docks on that day? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No—I do not know on what day this brandy was put on board the <hi rend="italic">Honduras.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440819-name-1109" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1109" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1109" type="surname" value="CAPPS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1109" type="given" value="SAMPSON"></interp>SAMPSON CAPPS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a dipping-officer. When these brandies were in the St. Katherine's Dock I re-dipped them all, and delivered six casks—I have got the marks here—"D. G." with "O." under, from No. 1 to 6—they were what we call "quarter casks"—they were all right in point of quantity when I examined them.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Did you see them put on board the <hi rend="italic">Honduras</hi>? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440819-name-1110" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1110" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1110" type="surname" value="STEVENS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1110" type="given" value="NATHANIEL"></interp>NATHANIEL STEVENS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a re-dipping officer of the London Docks. On the 9th of July I received an order to deliver some casks of brandy—four of them were marked "N. D." in a diamond, from 956 to 959 inclusive, which was the export mark—they were from the Duren, and sent to the <hi rend="italic">Honduras</hi>—I re-dipped them at the time of delivery—the No. "957 N. G." contained 56 gallons, and those four with the "S." contained 57 gallons.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440819-name-1111" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1111" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1111" type="surname" value="BEALBY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1111" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN BEALBY</persName>
                  </hi>. I am foreman at the East Quay, at the London Docks. On</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184408190175"></xptr>
               <p>the 9th of July I delivered some casks marked "N. D." in a diamond, from 956 to 959, to Lucy's craft—on the 1st of Aug. I delivered two casks of brandy "S. 2 and 4," into Saye's craft—the name of the vessel was not mentioned—the contents marked are on the casks, but they are re-dipped, and there is a difference sometimes.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440819-name-1112" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1112" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1112" type="surname" value="GOODING"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1112" type="given" value="ROBERT"></interp>ROBERT GOODING</persName>
                  </hi>. I am in the employ of Mr. Charles Lucy, a lighter<lb></lb>man. On the 3rd of Aug. I delivered from his boat six casks of brandy, four marked "N. D." in a diamond, and two were "S."—there were no spill or auger holes in them.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Did you go on board the <hi rend="italic">Honduras</hi>? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—I cannot say how many men were on board—there might be six or nine on deck, and three or four men below.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <rs id="t18440819-2132-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
                        <interp inst="t18440819-2132-verdict-1" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440819-2132-verdict-1" type="verdictSubcategory" value="no_subcategory"></interp>GUILTY</rs>
                  </hi>.* Aged 29.—<hi rend="italic">
                     <rs id="t18440819-2132-punishment-206" type="punishmentDescription">
                        <interp inst="t18440819-2132-punishment-206" type="punishmentCategory" value="transport"></interp>
                        <join result="defendantPunishment" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-2132-18440819 t18440819-2132-punishment-206"></join>Transported for Ten Years</rs>.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Sixth Jury, before <persName id="t18440819-name-1113" type="judiciaryName">
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1113" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1113" type="surname" value="BULLOCK"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1113" type="given" value="EDWARD"></interp>Edward Bullock</persName>, Esq.</hi>
